"""
MKT Original — 2 Samuel chapters 4–7
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-2samuel-4-7-full.py

Ch4:  Assassination of Ishbosheth; David's justice (12 verses)
Ch5:  All Israel anoints David; capture of Jerusalem; Philistine wars (25 verses)
Ch6:  Ark brought to Jerusalem; Uzzah's death; David dances; Michal (23 verses)
Ch7:  Nathan's oracle; Davidic covenant; David's prayer (29 verses — v12 already exists)

Key Hebrew lexical terms:
- ʿeṣem ûḇāśār (bone and flesh, 5:1) — kinship solidarity formula
- nāgîḏ (designated leader, 5:2; 7:8) vs. melek (king)
- YHWH Ṣĕḇāʾôṯ (5:10) — first use in 2 Samuel; divine warrior epithet
- Zion (ṣiyyôn, 5:7) — first occurrence; theological geography
- ʾārôn hāʾĕlōhîm / ʾārôn YHWH (ark vocabulary throughout ch6)
- ʿōz / šāgāh (irreverence/error vs. deliberate sin, 6:7) — Uzzah's death
- lûṣ / pāraṣ (contemptible/burst through, 6:20,22) — Michal confrontation
- bayit (house/dynasty/temple, 7:1-16) — triple semantic range
- zāraʿ (seed/offspring, 7:12) — messianic seed term
- kûn (establish/confirm, 7:12,13,16) — covenant-security term
- ḥeseḏ (steadfast love, 7:15) — covenant loyalty withheld from Saul but promised to David's heir
- ʿôlām (forever/eternal, 7:13,16,24,25,26,29) — six occurrences in ch7
- the father-son formula (7:14): ʾăni ʾehyeh-lô lĕʾāḇ wĕhûʾ yihyeh-lî lĕḇēn
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ORIGINAL = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p><em>wayyirpu yāḏāyw</em>: &#8216;his hands became feeble/slack&#8217; — the idiom for loss of courage and fighting capacity (Jer 38:4; Ezek 21:7; Isa 35:3). Ishbosheth&#8217;s collapse on hearing of Abner&#8217;s death shows the puppet king&#8217;s total dependence on Abner&#8217;s military and political support. &#8216;All Israel was dismayed&#8217; (<em>niḇhălû</em>, H926, terrified/confused) — the same root used for the terror of enemies before YHWH&#8217;s action. The house of Saul&#8217;s final disintegration begins with a single piece of news about its last pillar.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The two commanders (<em>śārê gĕḏûḏîm</em>, commanders of raiding parties) Baanah and Rechab are identified with precision — named, patronymized, and tribally located. The sons of Rimmon the Beerothite: Beeroth was a Gibeonite city (Josh 9:17) incorporated into Benjamin, whose inhabitants were driven out and became resident aliens. The political instability of the Benjaminite fringe — non-native commanders serving a weakening king — sets up their murderous calculation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The parenthetical note that the Beerothites &#8216;fled to Gittaim and lived there as resident foreigners (<em>gērîm</em>) to this day&#8217; explains a displacement event and signals the Beerothites&#8217; liminal status. <em>Gēr</em> (H1616, resident alien/sojourner) carried specific legal protections in Israelite law (Exod 22:21; Lev 19:34; Deut 24:17-18) — YHWH identifies with the <em>gēr</em> as one he specially protects. The narrator&#8217;s &#8216;to this day&#8217; (<em>ʿaḏ hayyôm hazzeh</em>) is an etiological marker connecting a historical event to a still-visible state of affairs in the narrator&#8217;s own time.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The narrative pauses for Mephibosheth: Jonathan&#8217;s son, lame in both feet, five years old when the news of Jezreel came. This parenthetical is inserted at the collapse of Saul&#8217;s house because Mephibosheth is the sole surviving heir — and David&#8217;s covenant with Jonathan (1 Sam 20:15-16) requires his protection when the rival dynasty falls. <em>Mĕpîḇōšeṯ</em> (alternate: <em>mĕrîḇ-baʿal</em>, 1 Chr 8:34 — baal is replaced with <em>bōšeṯ</em>, shame, in the anti-Baal name-editing of later tradition). His lameness is introduced here as the social vulnerability that makes David&#8217;s later covenant loyalty to him (2 Sam 9) the more significant act of grace.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The assassins arrive at Ishbosheth&#8217;s house &#8216;during the heat of the day&#8217; (<em>ḥōm hayyôm</em>) — midday when activity stops and guards are slack (cf. 1 Kgs 20:16; the same phrase in Gen 18:1 for Abraham&#8217;s midday encounter with the three visitors). The tactic of arriving under the pretense of bringing wheat (<em>ḥiṭṭîm</em>) exploits the normal agricultural commerce that would gain admission to a household compound. The weaponized ordinary transaction is the assassination technique — using routine economic activity as cover for lethal intent.</p>",
    "6": "<p>They slip into the interior of the house under the wheat-gathering pretense and stab him in the belly (<em>hammĕṣ</em>, the fifth, i.e., the abdomen). The intimate, indoor assassination of the king on his midday rest is the extreme violation of both hospitality and royal protection protocols. The detailed narration emphasizes the premeditation and treachery — facts David will cite in his judgment speech. The anatomy-specific murder (belly wound) contrasts with the honorable battlefield deaths the narrative otherwise records.</p>",
    "7": "<p>They struck him (<em>wayyakkuhû waymîṯuhû wĕyāqōzzû ʾet-rōʾšô</em>): killed him and cut off his head — and traveled through the Arabah all night, the route from Transjordan to Hebron. The beheading of the enemy king and transport of the head to the victor follows ANE military conventions (cf. 1 Sam 17:51; 31:9-10 — both involving Saul&#8217;s house). They calculate that David will reward them for eliminating his rival; instead he will execute them for the murder of YHWH&#8217;s anointed.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;Here is the head of Ishbosheth son of Saul, your enemy, who sought your life. Today YHWH has given my lord the king vengeance on Saul and his offspring.&#8221; The assassins frame their murder as YHWH&#8217;s action — a theodicy of political violence. The claim that YHWH executed vengeance through their act is the self-serving theological interpretation that David will explicitly reject. The verb <em>nāqam</em> (H5358, to avenge/take vengeance) — David has never sought vengeance against Saul&#8217;s house; the killers project onto David&#8217;s motives what was entirely their own calculation.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David&#8217;s oath formula: <em>ḥay YHWH ʾăšer pāḏāh ʾet-napšî mikol-ṣārāh</em> — &#8216;As YHWH lives, who has redeemed (<em>pāḏāh</em>, H6299) my life from every affliction.&#8217; The verb <em>pāḏāh</em> (to ransom/redeem by payment) — used for the ransom of the firstborn (Exod 13:13-15; Num 18:15-16), and for YHWH&#8217;s redemption of Israel from Egypt (Deut 7:8; 9:26; 13:5; 2 Sam 7:23). David grounds his oath in YHWH as the one who has been his personal redeemer — the theological attribution that gives the following judgment its divine authority.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David cites the precedent: the Amalekite at Ziklag (2 Sam 1:1-16) who reported Saul&#8217;s death, thinking he was bringing &#8216;good news&#8217; (<em>mĕḇaśśēr</em>, H1319 — to announce glad tidings, the root of <em>bĕśôrāh</em>/gospel). David had the man executed despite his claim that Saul had asked to be killed. The legal precedent David invokes: even if Saul deserved death, the killer of YHWH&#8217;s anointed is not rewarded. The pattern of David refusing to receive the anointed&#8217;s death as &#8216;good news&#8217; from those who caused it runs consistently through chs 1-4.</p>",
    "11": "<p><em>ʾanāšîm rĕšāʿîm ʾăšer hārĕgû ʾet-ʾîš ṣaddîq bĕḇêṯô ʿal-miškāḇô</em> — &#8216;wicked men who murdered a righteous man in his own house on his bed.&#8217; The contrast between <em>rāšāʿ</em> (wicked) and <em>ṣaddîq</em> (righteous) in David&#8217;s verdict identifies the murder in covenantal terms: Ishbosheth, however politically weak, was a &#8216;righteous man&#8217; (<em>ṣaddîq</em>) in the sense of having done nothing deserving death. The question &#8216;should I not now require his blood from your hands?&#8217; (<em>hălōʾ ʾăḇaqqēš ʾet-dāmô miyyedĕkem</em>) uses <em>bāqaš</em> (to seek/require) — YHWH requires blood-guilt from those who shed innocent blood (Gen 9:5; 42:22).</p>",
    "12": "<p>David orders their execution and the cutting of their hands and feet — the body parts that acted in the murder — and the hanging of their bodies at the pool in Hebron. The mutilation of the executioners&#8217; hands (which killed) and feet (which carried them to Hebron) is the lex talionis principle applied with specificity. The public display at the pool of Hebron — David&#8217;s capital — serves the same justice-signaling function as the public display of Saul&#8217;s body at Beth-Shan (1 Sam 31:10): covenant justice visibly executed prevents the perception of impunity.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p><em>ʿaṣmênû ûḇĕśārênû ʾănaḥnû</em> — &#8216;We are your bone and your flesh.&#8217; The kinship-solidarity formula (<em>ʿeṣem ûḇāśār</em>) is the ancient Near Eastern bond of shared physical identity between persons who belong to the same clan or household. Laban uses it of Jacob (Gen 29:14); Abimelech&#8217;s men use it of their kin (Judg 9:2); David will use it of all Israel when he appeals for their return after Absalom&#8217;s defeat (2 Sam 19:12-13). The formula is the verbal enactment of covenant kinship: &#8216;we are one body.&#8217; All the tribes present themselves to David as his kin, dissolving the Ishbosheth-era tribal divisions.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&#8216;You were the one who led Israel out to battle and brought them home&#8217; — the language of military shepherding, using <em>yāṣāʾ wāḇôʾ</em> (going out and coming in) as the idiom for military leadership (Num 27:17; Deut 31:2; 1 Sam 18:16). The defining qualification they cite is practical: he was the effective military leader even when another was titular king. YHWH&#8217;s appointment: &#8216;You will shepherd (<em>tirʿeh</em>, H7462) my people Israel and will be ruler (<em>nāgîḏ</em>) over Israel.&#8217; The shepherding metaphor (<em>rāʿāh</em>) for kingship and the <em>nāgîḏ</em> designation (YHWH&#8217;s designated one, not merely a self-proclaimed king) both frame David&#8217;s rule in covenantal rather than political terms.</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>wayyikrot lāhem hammelek dāwid bĕrît bĕḥeḇrôn lip̄nê YHWH</em> — &#8216;King David made a covenant with them before YHWH.&#8217; The pan-Israelite anointing at Hebron is David&#8217;s third anointing: first by Samuel at Bethlehem (1 Sam 16:13), then by Judah at Hebron (2 Sam 2:4), now by all Israel at Hebron. Three anointings completing the <em>māšaḥ</em> (anointing) sequence — the threefold consecration establishing beyond all ambiguity that this is YHWH&#8217;s chosen king. The covenant (<em>bĕrîṯ</em>) made before YHWH frames the political union as a covenant relationship with YHWH as witness and guarantor.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David was thirty years old when he became king — the same age at which Levites began their sanctuary service (Num 4:3,23,30,35,39,43,47). Josephus interprets this as a providential alignment. Jesus begins his ministry at &#8216;about thirty years of age&#8217; (Luke 3:23). Thirty as the age of public inauguration for covenantal service — the Levitical completion of formation, the Davidic beginning of reign, the messianic commencement of ministry — is a consistent pattern. David&#8217;s total reign is forty years: seven and a half in Hebron over Judah, thirty-three in Jerusalem over all Israel.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The precision of seven years and six months in Hebron vs. thirty-three years in Jerusalem encodes the theology of the unified monarchy: the majority of the reign is from Zion, the city that YHWH will choose. The numbers 7.5 + 33 = 40.5, typically rounded to 40 — the covenant number of completeness (forty years in the wilderness; forty days of Moses on Sinai; forty days of Jesus in the wilderness). David&#8217;s reign is shaped by the covenant arithmetic of complete faithfulness within YHWH&#8217;s appointed duration.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Jebusites taunt: &#8216;You will not get in here; even the blind and the lame can ward you off.&#8217; (<em>lōʾ-tāḇôʾ hēnnāh kî ʾim-hĕsîrĕḵā hāʿiwwĕrîm wĕhappissĕḥîm</em>). The phrase has generated multiple interpretations for the cryptic proverb &#8216;the blind and the lame will keep David out.&#8217; The Jebusites&#8217; mockery claims the city&#8217;s natural defenses are so strong that even the physically disabled defenders could hold it. The taunt is answered by David&#8217;s capture — YHWH&#8217;s ironic reversal: the city that cannot be taken is taken; the despised king takes the &#8216;untakeable&#8217; stronghold.</p>",
    "7": "<p><em>wayyilkoḏ dāwid ʾet-mĕṣuḏaṯ ṣiyyôn hîʾ ʿîr dāwid</em> — &#8216;David captured the stronghold of Zion; this is the city of David.&#8217; The first occurrence of <em>ṣiyyôn</em> (H6726, Zion) in the historical narrative establishes the theological geography that will dominate the OT and NT: the mount of YHWH&#8217;s presence, the place of the ark, the city of the anointed king. The identification of Zion with &#8216;the city of David&#8217; (<em>ʿîr dāwid</em>) links the cosmic sanctuary-mountain with the Davidic covenant — this place belongs to the anointed king and his line.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8216;Whoever attacks the Jebusites must go up through the water tunnel (<em>ṣinnôr</em>)&#8217; — the water-shaft that Warren&#8217;s archaeological exploration in 1867 identified as the access to Jerusalem&#8217;s water supply. The technical term <em>ṣinnôr</em> (H6794, conduit/water-shaft) is unique here; its meaning has been debated. The narrator adds: &#8216;Therefore they say, the blind and the lame shall not enter the house&#8217; — an etiological note connecting the anti-Jebusite taunt to a post-conquest proverb. The water-shaft entrance is the hidden access through which the impossible capture became possible — a detail that resonates with the OT pattern of YHWH using unexpected means to accomplish his purposes.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David occupies the stronghold and calls it <em>ʿîr dāwid</em> (the city of David), then builds up the city from the <em>millōʾ</em> (H4407, filling/terrace, the retaining wall system) inward. The <em>millōʾ</em> appears repeatedly as a major construction element in Jerusalem (1 Kgs 9:15,24; 11:27; 2 Kgs 12:20) — apparently a large platform or terrace supporting the upper city structures. Jerusalem&#8217;s topography required massive earthwork to create buildable surfaces; David begins the infrastructure that Solomon will complete.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>wayyēleḵ dāwid hālôḵ wĕgāḏôl waYHWH ʾĕlōhê ṣĕḇāʾôṯ ʿimmô</em> — &#8216;David grew steadily greater, for YHWH God of hosts was with him.&#8217; The divine presence formula — &#8216;YHWH was with him&#8217; (<em>ʿimmô</em>) — is the consistent theological explanation for David&#8217;s prosperity (1 Sam 16:18; 18:14; 2 Sam 7:3,9). <em>YHWH ʾĕlōhê ṣĕḇāʾôṯ</em> (YHWH God of Hosts) — the full title emphasizing the divine warrior who commands the heavenly armies — first sustained use here in 2 Samuel, reflecting the military context of Jerusalem&#8217;s capture and the Philistine defeats to follow.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Hiram king of Tyre sends cedar timber (<em>ʾarzê halĕḇānôn</em>), carpenters, and stonemasons, and builds David&#8217;s palace. The Phoenician craftsmen and materials that will be central to Solomon&#8217;s temple-building (1 Kgs 5-7) begin here with the royal palace. Cedar (<em>ʾerez</em>, H730) — the prestige building material of the ancient Near East, its fragrance and durability associated with royalty throughout the region — signals David&#8217;s elevation to peer-king status recognized by the major Levantine trading power.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>wayyēḏaʿ dāwid kî-hĕkînô YHWH lĕmelek ʿal-yiśrāʾēl wĕkî niśśēʾ mamlaktô baʿăḇûr ʿammô yiśrāʾēl</em> — &#8216;David recognized that YHWH had established (<em>hĕkîn</em>, H3559 — from <em>kûn</em>, to establish/confirm/make firm) him as king over Israel and had elevated (<em>niśśēʾ</em>) his kingdom for the sake of his people Israel.&#8217; The verb <em>kûn</em> (to establish/confirm) is the key term of the Davidic covenant that will appear six times in ch7. David&#8217;s theological recognition — connecting his establishment to YHWH&#8217;s purpose for Israel rather than personal achievement — is the covenant-consciousness that characterizes his kingship.</p>",
    "13": "<p>David takes more concubines and wives in Jerusalem; more sons and daughters are born. The royal harem expansion in Jerusalem is both a political act (alliances) and a covenant warning — the law of the king in Deut 17:17 prohibits the king from multiplying wives (<em>lōʾ yarbeh-lô nāšîm</em>). The narrator records without comment what will become a source of crisis: Solomon&#8217;s foreign wives who turn his heart (1 Kgs 11:1-8) and Absalom&#8217;s future violation of David&#8217;s concubines (2 Sam 16:21-22) are seeds planted here. The king who multiplies what the Torah prohibits is sowing for a later harvest.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The list of David&#8217;s sons born in Jerusalem begins with Shammua, Shobab, Nathan, Solomon (<em>šĕmôʿāh, šôḇāḇ, nāṯān, šĕlōmōh</em>). <em>Nāṯān</em> (Nathan, &#8216;he has given&#8217;) — not the prophet but a son — will appear in Luke 3:31 as an ancestor of Mary in the Lukan genealogy, providing the non-Solomonic Davidic line through which Christ&#8217;s legal Davidic descent passes on the maternal side. <em>Šĕlōmōh</em> (Solomon, from <em>šālôm</em>, peace) — his name encoding the peace-era covenant blessing — will be the immediate fulfillment of the Davidic covenant promise.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The list of David&#8217;s Jerusalem sons continues: Ibhar, Elishua, Nepheg, and Japhia. <em>ʾelîšûaʿ</em> (Elishua, &#8216;my God is salvation&#8217;) — another throne-name encoding theology; <em>ʾelîšāmaʿ</em> and <em>ʾelîyāḏāʿ</em> (vv16-17) similarly encode the divine name with covenantal attributes. Royal name-theology in the ancient Near East embedded the king&#8217;s relationship to the deity in the names of his sons — these are not random names but theological declarations about YHWH&#8217;s relationship to the Davidic house.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Elishama, Eliada, and Eliphelet complete the Jerusalem-born sons list. <em>ʾelîyāḏāʿ</em> (Eliada, &#8216;God has known&#8217;, H450) uses the covenant-knowledge verb <em>yāḏaʿ</em> — the same verb in YHWH&#8217;s covenant formula &#8216;you only have I known (<em>yāḏaʿtî</em>) of all the families of the earth&#8217; (Amos 3:2). The royal sons&#8217; names encode the covenant relationship between YHWH and the Davidic house: God knows, God is salvation, God has given. These names are a liturgical confession distributed across the royal household.</p>",
    "17": "<p>When the Philistines heard that David had been anointed king over Israel, &#8216;all the Philistines went up to search for David&#8217; — the anointing triggers the military threat. The same pattern as Jesus: at the announcement of his birth, Herod sends soldiers (Matt 2:16); at his baptism-anointing, the Spirit drives him into the wilderness for the Satan-confrontation (Mark 1:12). The anointing of YHWH&#8217;s king is the signal for the powers opposed to the covenant to mobilize. David&#8217;s inquiring of YHWH (v19) before engaging is the immediate covenant response.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The Philistines deploy in the Valley of Rephaim (<em>ʿemeq rĕpāʾîm</em>, H7497 — valley of the Rephaim). The Rephaim were the pre-Israelite giant warriors of Canaan (Deut 2:11,20; 3:11,13) — the valley associated with their remnants is the site of both Philistine deployments (vv18 and 22). The choice of this valley may signal the Philistines&#8217; alignment with the ancient enemies of Israel&#8217;s inheritance, or may simply be the tactically favorable position. David&#8217;s two victories here demonstrate that YHWH has indeed &#8216;burst through&#8217; the enemies of his anointed.</p>",
    "19": "<p><em>wayyišʾal dāwid baYHWH lēʾmōr haʾeʿăleh ʾel-pĕlištîm</em> — &#8216;David inquired of YHWH: shall I go up against the Philistines?&#8217; The formal consultation of YHWH before military action — using the oracle mechanism (<em>šāʾal</em>, H7592, to ask/inquire) — is the consistent marker of covenant-dependent leadership. Saul&#8217;s failure at the same point (1 Sam 28: Saul cannot get an answer from YHWH and turns to the medium) is the negative foil. YHWH&#8217;s answer is direct: <em>ʿălēh kî nāṯōn ʾettēn ʾet-happĕlištîm bĕyāḏeḵā</em> — the double infinitive absolute &#8216;I will certainly give&#8217; indicates emphatic certainty.</p>",
    "20": "<p><em>pāraṣ YHWH ʾet-ʾōyĕḇay lĕp̄ānay kĕp̄ereṣ mayim</em> — &#8216;YHWH has burst through (<em>pāraṣ</em>, H6555) my enemies before me like a bursting of waters.&#8217; The verb <em>pāraṣ</em> (to break through/burst out) conveys irresistible forward movement — the same root in &#8216;may you break out (<em>ûp̄āraṣtā</em>)&#8217; of the promise to Jacob (Gen 28:14). The name Baal-Perazim (&#8216;Lord of breaking through&#8217;) is the site-naming that memorializes YHWH&#8217;s action. David attributes the victory entirely to YHWH&#8217;s agency: he interprets his military success as YHWH breaking through, not David conquering.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Philistines abandon their idols (<em>ʿaṣabbêhem</em>, H6091 — idols, from a root meaning carved/shaped). David and his men carry them off (<em>wayyiśśāʾēm</em>). The reversal is pointed: in 1 Sam 5-6 the Philistines had captured the ark of YHWH and found YHWH&#8217;s superiority demonstrated by the Dagon-disaster; now David captures their idols. The direction of trophy-taking has reversed: in the time of Eli the ark went to Philistia; now the Philistine idols come to Israel. The anointed king&#8217;s victory is measured in the trophies of the defeated powers.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The Philistines come up a second time to the Valley of Rephaim. The repetition of the attack after the first defeat tests whether David will again inquire of YHWH or trust his previous tactics. The consistent inquiry-before-action pattern is the model for covenant-dependent leadership — never assuming past success authorizes present action without fresh divine guidance. Saul&#8217;s pattern was repetition of previous tactics; David&#8217;s pattern is fresh inquiry each time.</p>",
    "23": "<p>YHWH&#8217;s different tactical instruction for the second battle — &#8216;Do not go straight up; circle around behind them and come at them from in front of the balsam trees (<em>bĕkāʾîm</em>)&#8217; — demonstrates the non-mechanical nature of YHWH&#8217;s guidance. The same enemy, the same valley, a completely different tactic. <em>Bākāʾ</em> trees (H1057, probably balsam or mastic trees) — the wind-movement in their tops will be the supernatural signal. YHWH&#8217;s sovereignty over tactics means each engagement requires fresh obedience, not tactical formulaic repetition.</p>",
    "24": "<p><em>bĕšomʿăḵā ʾet-qôl ṣĕʿāḏāh bĕrāʾšê habbĕkāʾîm</em> — &#8216;When you hear the sound of marching in the tops of the balsam trees, then act decisively, for YHWH has gone out before you.&#8217; The audible supernatural signal — YHWH&#8217;s army marching in the treetops — is the divine guarantee of victory announced before battle. The divine warrior going out before the army (<em>yāṣāʾ lip̄nêḵā</em>) is the theophanic-war pattern: YHWH as the true military commander whose presence precedes the human army. The divine sound in the trees is the audible manifestation of the cosmic war that underlies every covenant military engagement.</p>",
    "25": "<p>David does as YHWH commanded and strikes the Philistines from Geba to Gezer — the full extent of the Philistine deployment zone in the central Shephelah corridor. &#8216;As YHWH commanded him&#8217; (<em>kaʾăšer ṣiwwāh YHWH</em>) — the fulfillment-of-command formula that validates the preceding divine instruction. The bracket &#8216;YHWH commanded&#8217; (v23) and &#8216;David did as YHWH commanded&#8217; (v25) encloses the battle account: the human action is the execution of the divine word, not independent military initiative.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>David assembles thirty thousand chosen men (<em>kol-bĕḥûr bĕyiśrāʾēl šĕlōšîm ʾālep̄</em>) for the ark transport. The number thirty thousand — the same as the Israelite levy that died with the ark in 1 Sam 4:10 — is not coincidental: this is the full covenant assembly, the restoration of what was lost when the ark was captured. The scale signals that this is not a military expedition but a covenant ceremony of national importance.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David sets out &#8216;from Baale-judah&#8217; (= Kiriath-jearim, 1 Chr 13:6) to bring up the ark of God, &#8216;which is called by the name, the name of YHWH of hosts who sits enthroned on the cherubim.&#8217; The full divine name formula attached to the ark — <em>YHWH ṣĕḇāʾôṯ yōšēḇ hakkĕrūḇîm</em> — identifies the ark as YHWH&#8217;s throne-presence. The cherubim-enthroned YHWH is the divine warrior king seated between the golden cherubim of the mercy seat; bringing the ark to Jerusalem is bringing the divine king to his royal city.</p>",
    "3": "<p>They place the ark on a new cart (<em>ʿăgālāh ḥăḏāšāh</em>) — precisely the mistake that the previous ark transport made (1 Sam 6:7: the Philistines used a new cart). The Mosaic law specified that the Kohathites were to carry the ark on their shoulders with poles (Num 4:15; 7:9); using a cart was the Philistine method, adapted from the Philistine return. The use of the &#8216;new cart&#8217; signals that David&#8217;s first attempt is following Philistine protocol rather than Mosaic prescription — a syncretism that will prove deadly.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Uzzah and Ahio drive the cart from Abinadab&#8217;s house. Ahio walks in front (<em>lĕp̄ānāyw</em>) of the ark — the proper ceremonial position for the procession leader. The narrative&#8217;s double-mention of the cart and the personnel (vv3-4) sets up the tension: everything looks correct — new cart, authorized handlers, celebratory procession — but the method is wrong, and the theological crisis will reveal the error.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David and all Israel celebrate before YHWH with all kinds of instruments — <em>bĕkol-ʿăṣê bĕrôšîm wĕḇĕkinnōrôṯ ûḇĕnĕḇālîm ûḇĕṯuppîm ûḇĕmĕnāʿanĕʿîm ûḇĕṣeliṣalîm</em> (fir/cypress wood instruments, lyres, harps, tambourines, rattles, cymbals). The comprehensive musical listing parallels the Psalter&#8217;s instrument inventories (Ps 150). The contrast between the celebratory atmosphere and the imminent crisis underscores the narrative&#8217;s theological point: sincere enthusiasm is not the same as covenant obedience.</p>",
    "6": "<p>When they reach the threshing floor of Nacon (<em>gōren nāḵôn</em>), the oxen stumble (<em>šāmĕṭû</em>, H8058 — slipped/stumbled) and Uzzah reaches out and grabs the ark of God. The verb <em>ʾāḥaz</em> (H270, to seize/grab) describes an act of apparent service — preventing the ark from falling. The problem is that the touching itself is the violation: Num 4:15 explicitly prohibits the Kohathites from touching the holy things on pain of death (<em>lōʾ-yiggĕʿû ʾel-haqqōḏeš wāmēṯû</em>). The ark&#8217;s holiness is not conditional on whether it is in danger of falling.</p>",
    "7": "<p><em>wayyiḥar-ʾap̄ YHWH bĕʿuzzāh wayyakkēhû šām hāʾĕlōhîm ʿal-haššal</em> — &#8216;The anger of YHWH flared against Uzzah, and God struck him down there for his irreverence (<em>ʾal-haššal</em>).&#8217; The term <em>šal</em> (H7944, a hapax legomenon — irreverence, audacity, mishandling) is unique; interpretations range from &#8216;rashness&#8217; to &#8216;the mistake.&#8217; Whatever the precise nuance, the death is covenantal: YHWH&#8217;s holiness is not suspended by good intentions. The ark is YHWH&#8217;s holy throne; no human hand may touch it. The severity of the response establishes that covenant protocol cannot be improvised.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David is angry (<em>wayyiḥar lĕdāwid</em>) at YHWH&#8217;s striking of Uzzah. The same verb (<em>ḥārah</em>, H2734, to burn/flare with anger) used for YHWH&#8217;s anger in v7 is now used for David&#8217;s anger — a mirror structure. The name given: <em>Perez-Uzzah</em> (&#8216;the breaking-out against Uzzah&#8217;, from <em>pāraṣ</em>, to break through) — the same <em>pāraṣ</em> David had just used in praise (v20: &#8216;YHWH has burst through my enemies like a bursting of waters&#8217;). YHWH&#8217;s <em>pāraṣ</em> in battle is victory; YHWH&#8217;s <em>pāraṣ</em> against Uzzah is judgment. The same divine attribute operates in both directions.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David is afraid of YHWH that day (<em>wayyîrāʾ dāwid ʾet-YHWH</em>) and asks: &#8216;How can the ark of YHWH come to me?&#8217; The <em>yārēʾ</em> (fear) here is the appropriate covenant response to YHWH&#8217;s holiness in action — not terror that paralyzes but the reverential recognition that YHWH is holy and the approach to him must be on his terms. Qohelet&#8217;s summary: &#8216;Fear God and keep his commandments&#8217; (Eccl 12:13). David&#8217;s question is the right question: on what terms can the holy God come to me? The answer will require learning the proper transport method.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David diverts the ark to the house of Obed-edom the Gittite (<em>ʾeḏôm haggittî</em>). The Gittite identification (from Gath) — a foreigner from Philistine territory — is notable: the ark that drove the Philistines to disaster (1 Sam 5-6) now blesses a Gittite&#8217;s household. The same divine presence that is dangerous when approached incorrectly is a source of extraordinary blessing when hosted properly. The covenant pattern: YHWH&#8217;s holiness is not domesticated by association with the foreigner who receives it rightly.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The ark stays at Obed-edom&#8217;s house for three months, and YHWH blesses his household and everything he has. The three-month blessing of Obed-edom while David has withdrawn in fear demonstrates what the ark&#8217;s presence was meant to produce: covenant blessing for the covenant community. The blessing that should have come to Jerusalem via David is instead coming to a Gittite&#8217;s house — a pointed reversal that motivates David&#8217;s second attempt with proper protocol.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>wayyuggaḏ lammelek dāwid lēʾmōr bēraḵ YHWH ʾet-bêṯ ʾōḇēḏ-ʾeḏôm wĕʾet-kol-ʾăšer-lô baʿăḇûr ʾărôn hāʾĕlōhîm</em> — &#8216;YHWH has blessed the household of Obed-edom and everything belonging to him, on account of the ark of God.&#8217; The reported blessing motivates David&#8217;s return for the ark. His going to bring up the ark from Obed-edom&#8217;s house &#8216;with joy&#8217; (<em>bĕśimḥāh</em>) — this time, 1 Chr 15:2 records, with Levites carrying it on their shoulders as Moses commanded. The text here does not specify the change of protocol; the Chronicles parallel provides the correction that explains the successful completion.</p>",
    "13": "<p>When those carrying the ark had gone six paces, David sacrificed an ox and a fattened calf. The sacrificial offering at the six-pace mark — a near-immediate offering after the procession begins successfully — marks the contrast with the previous failed attempt. The six-pace sacrifice is a thanksgiving that the ark is moving properly. The number six may be symbolic (creation week minus Sabbath rest) or simply the safe-distance that confirms YHWH&#8217;s acceptance of the revised protocol. David&#8217;s immediate offering connects the joyful procession to the sacrificial system.</p>",
    "14": "<p><em>wĕdāwid mĕkarker bĕkol-ʿōz lip̄nê YHWH wĕdāwid ḥāgûr ʾēp̄ôḏ bāḏ</em> — &#8216;David danced before YHWH with all his strength, wearing a linen ephod.&#8217; <em>Kārar</em> (H3769, to whirl/dance in a circle) is an intense, full-bodied dance expression; &#8216;with all his strength&#8217; (<em>bĕkol-ʿōz</em>) emphasizes complete physical investment. The linen ephod (<em>ʾēp̄ôḏ bāḏ</em>) is the priestly garment — not the elaborate high-priestly ephod of Exod 28 but the simpler linen garment of priestly service (cf. Samuel in 1 Sam 2:18). David dances in priestly garb, blurring the royal-priestly distinction in a way that anticipates the Psalm 110 melchizedekian priest-king.</p>",
    "15": "<p>All the house of Israel brings up the ark with shouting (<em>bîrûʿāh</em>, H8643 — the covenant war-shout that is simultaneously a liturgical acclaim) and the sound of the ram&#8217;s horn (<em>šôp̄ār</em>, H7782). The <em>tĕrûʿāh</em> (shout) is the sound of YHWH&#8217;s kingship — used at Sinai (Exod 19:19: the sound of the trumpet), at Jericho (Josh 6:5), and throughout the Psalms of Ascent. The ark&#8217;s entrance into Zion with this shout is the original of the Psalm 24 liturgy: &#8216;Lift up your heads, O gates... that the King of glory may come in. Who is this King of glory? YHWH of hosts — he is the King of glory!&#8217;</p>",
    "16": "<p>Michal daughter of Saul looks down through the window and sees David leaping and dancing before YHWH, and she despises him in her heart (<em>wattiḇez lô bĕlibbāh</em>). The window-gazing Michal seeing the king and despising him is a visual rhyme with 1 Sam 18:28 where the verb of seeing and loving was used of her: the love has become contempt. <em>Bāzāh</em> (H959, to despise/treat with contempt) — the same verb used for Esau&#8217;s contempt of his birthright (Gen 25:34), for despising YHWH&#8217;s offering (1 Sam 2:17). The daughter of Saul applies Saul&#8217;s characteristic contempt for covenant worship to David&#8217;s priestly dance.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The ark is set in its place inside the tent David had pitched for it, and David offers burnt offerings and peace offerings before YHWH. The narrative sequence: ark installed → sacrifices offered → blessing of the people (v18) → distribution of bread, meat, and raisins (v19) → departure. This is the covenant feast structure: sanctuary installation, sacrifice, blessing, shared meal. It mirrors the covenant meal at Sinai (Exod 24:9-11: the elders saw God and ate and drank) and anticipates the Psalm 22 promise: &#8216;Those who fear him will praise him... the afflicted shall eat and be satisfied&#8217; (Ps 22:24-26).</p>",
    "18": "<p><em>waykǎl dāwid mehāʿălôṯ hāʿōlāh wĕhašĕlāmîm wayyĕḇāreḵ ʾet-hāʿām bĕšēm YHWH ṣĕḇāʾôṯ</em> — &#8216;When David had finished offering burnt offerings and peace offerings, he blessed the people in the name of YHWH of hosts.&#8217; The priestly blessing of the people — &#8216;in the name of YHWH of hosts&#8217; — is the kingly-priestly function David exercises: the king who blesses the covenant community through the divine name. Num 6:22-27: the Aaronic blessing ends with &#8216;they shall put my name on the Israelites, and I will bless them.&#8217; David&#8217;s blessing mediates YHWH&#8217;s name to the assembled covenant community.</p>",
    "19": "<p>David distributes to every person in Israel — men and women alike — a round loaf of bread (<em>ḥallat-leḥem</em>), a portion of roasted meat (<em>ʾešpār</em>), and a raisin cake (<em>ʾăšîšāh</em>). The distribution to &#8216;men and women alike&#8217; (<em>lĕkol-hāʾām lĕkol-hāmôn yiśrāʾēl</em>) — the entire covenant community without distinction — is the covenant meal as universal distribution. The three food items: bread (the staple of covenant life), meat (the sacrificial portion), and raisins (the fruit of the promised land). The king distributing the covenant feast to the entire people is the pattern that Jesus executes in the feeding of the five thousand (John 6:11) and formalizes in the Last Supper.</p>",
    "20": "<p>David returns to bless his household; Michal comes out to meet him and says: &#8216;How the king of Israel distinguished himself today — exposing himself to the eyes of slave girls as any shameless person might do!&#8217; <em>Qālal</em> (H7043, to treat as light/contemptible/curse) — to make oneself light, low, despicable. Michal&#8217;s accusation is that David&#8217;s undignified dance <em>qillēl</em> (made contemptible) the royal office. She uses the language of ritual impurity and social shame. Her contempt is for the form of the worship rather than its substance.</p>",
    "21": "<p>David&#8217;s response: &#8216;It was before YHWH, who chose me (<em>bāḥar bî</em>) rather than your father and his whole house, to appoint me as ruler (<em>nāgîḏ</em>) over YHWH&#8217;s people Israel — I will celebrate before YHWH.&#8217; The covenantal grounding of the dance: before YHWH who <em>chose</em> me. David&#8217;s worship is the response to divine election, not a performance for human approval. The contrast with Saul&#8217;s house is explicit: YHWH chose David rather than Saul. The <em>nāgîḏ</em> designation is deliberately used — YHWH&#8217;s designated-one, not the self-asserting king.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&#8216;I will make myself yet more contemptible (<em>qālôṯî</em>, same root as Michal&#8217;s accusation) than this, and I will be humble in my own sight.&#8221; David accepts Michal&#8217;s accusation and doubles it: yes, he will be even more self-lowering. The <em>šāp̄āl</em> (to be low/humble in one&#8217;s own eyes) is the posture of Deut 17:20 for the king — not to lift his heart above his brothers. David&#8217;s willingness to be seen as undignified before YHWH is the embodiment of the covenant king who serves YHWH rather than his own royal image. &#8216;But by the slave girls you spoke of — by them I will be honored.&#8217; Those who witness the dance from below honor him precisely because of what Michal despises.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Michal daughter of Saul had no child to the day of her death (<em>lōʾ-hāyāh lāh yeleḏ ʿaḏ yôm môṯāh</em>). The barrenness as covenant judgment on her contempt for YHWH&#8217;s worship closes the Michal-Saul contrast: the daughter who despised the ark&#8217;s arrival with the royal contempt of her father&#8217;s house receives the covenant curse of childlessness that terminates Saul&#8217;s dynastic connection through David. The Saulide line through Michal ends; the Davidic line continues through others. The narrative of the barren woman has two sides: Hannah&#8217;s barrenness lifted when she consecrated her son; Michal&#8217;s barrenness is imposed because she despised covenant worship.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>David in his cedar palace, with YHWH giving him rest from his enemies (<em>hēnîaḥ lô YHWH misāḇîḇ mikkol-ʾōyĕḇāyw</em>). The <em>nûaḥ</em> (rest, H5117) — the covenantal sabbath-rest from enemies — is both the fulfillment of the Deuteronomic promise (Deut 12:10: &#8216;when he gives you rest from all your enemies&#8217;, then you will worship at the place YHWH chooses) and the precondition for the temple-building question. The irony: David&#8217;s sabbath-rest is the moment he wants to build YHWH a house — but YHWH will turn the conversation entirely.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David&#8217;s observation: &#8216;Look — I am living in a cedar house, but the ark of God is sitting within curtains (<em>yôšēḇ bĕṯôḵ hāyĕrîʿāh</em>).&#8217; The contrast between David&#8217;s opulent cedar palace (built by Hiram&#8217;s craftsmen, 5:11) and the ark&#8217;s tent-dwelling is the theological dissonance that motivates David&#8217;s temple proposal. The verb <em>yāšaḇ</em> (to dwell/sit) is used for both David in his house and the ark in the tent — they are both &#8216;dwelling,&#8217; but the king&#8217;s dwelling far exceeds the divine King&#8217;s. David&#8217;s motivation is reverence for YHWH&#8217;s honor.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Nathan&#8217;s initial approval — &#8216;Go, do all that is in your heart, for YHWH is with you&#8217; — is the prophet speaking from pastoral encouragement rather than from received revelation. The next verse reverses it: YHWH comes to Nathan in the night with a different answer. Nathan&#8217;s reversal (vv3-4) models the distinction between the prophet&#8217;s personal assessment (however well-intentioned) and the divine word (<em>dĕḇar YHWH</em>). The prophet who corrects his own previous counsel by the received word is more faithful than the prophet who cannot revise.</p>",
    "4": "<p><em>wayhî ballaylāh hahûʾ wayhî dĕḇar-YHWH ʾel-nāṯān</em> — &#8216;That night the word of YHWH came to Nathan.&#8217; The divine word arrives in the night — the same nighttime revelation pattern as Samuel&#8217;s call (1 Sam 3), Jacob&#8217;s dream at Bethel (Gen 28:12), and Joseph&#8217;s dreams (Gen 37). YHWH&#8217;s night-word to Nathan interrupts the course of the day&#8217;s human planning with the divine reorientation. The oracle that follows is the longest continuous divine speech in the Samuel narrative — a measure of its theological weight.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8216;Are you the one to build me a house (<em>habayit tibne-lî lāšāḇet</em>) to dwell in?&#8217; The divine question is the structural inversion of David&#8217;s offer: David will build YHWH a house; YHWH will build David a house. The word <em>bayit</em> (H1004, house/dynasty/household) will operate on three levels in the oracle: (1) the physical temple (&#8216;a house for my name&#8217;), (2) the dynastic household (&#8216;I will build you a house&#8217;), and (3) the covenantal family (&#8216;I will be his father and he will be my son&#8217;). YHWH&#8217;s reversal of the question is the most theologically generative play on a single word in the OT.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8216;I have not lived in a house from the day I brought the Israelites up from Egypt until today, but have moved about with a tent and a tabernacle (<em>bĕʾōhel ûḇĕmiškān</em>).&#8217; YHWH&#8217;s self-description as the God who moves with his people rather than being fixed in a permanent location is the theological corrective to David&#8217;s assumption. The tabernacle&#8217;s mobility — designed for the wilderness wandering — is not a deficiency to be remedied but a statement about the nature of YHWH&#8217;s presence: it accompanies the people wherever they go. The later Shekinah theology and John 1:14 (&#8216;the Word tabernacled among us&#8217;) recovers this mobile presence-theology.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8216;Everywhere I traveled with all the Israelites, did I ever say to any of the tribal leaders whom I commanded to shepherd my people Israel, &#8220;Why have you not built me a cedar house?&#8221;&#8217; YHWH never asked for permanence. The rhetorical question establishes that the temple-project is David&#8217;s initiative, not YHWH&#8217;s expressed need. This is not a rebuke of the temple-desire but a reorientation: YHWH&#8217;s own testimony about his past requests establishes that his dwelling in a tent was not a problem to be solved. The initiative for the temple comes from below, not from above.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8216;This is what YHWH of hosts says: I took you (<em>lāqaḥtîḵā</em>) from the pasture, from following the flock, to be ruler (<em>nāgîḏ</em>) over my people Israel.&#8217; The divine autobiography of election: YHWH took David from the sheep-pasture (<em>hannāweh</em>, H5116). The verb <em>lāqaḥ</em> (to take) is the election verb in covenant contexts — YHWH takes his chosen ones (Gen 12:1, Abraham taken from his land; Exod 6:7, Israel taken as YHWH&#8217;s people). The shepherd-to-king trajectory is the pattern that Psalm 78:70-72 celebrates: &#8216;He chose David his servant and took him from the sheep pens.&#8217;</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8216;I have been with you wherever you went and have cut off all your enemies before you, and I have made for you a great name (<em>šēm gāḏôl</em>) like the names of the greatest people on earth.&#8217; The <em>šēm gāḏôl</em> (great name) — the divine blessing formula first promised to Abraham (Gen 12:2: &#8216;I will make your name great&#8217;) is now extended to David. The Abrahamic blessing-of-the-nation flows through the Davidic king: the one who makes the nation&#8217;s name great is YHWH, who works through his chosen shepherd-king. David&#8217;s great name is YHWH&#8217;s gift, not human achievement.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8216;I will appoint a place (<em>māqôm</em>) for my people Israel and plant them there (<em>nĕṭaʿtîw</em>), so that they can have a home of their own and no longer be disturbed.&#8221; The planting-in-place image — Israel as a tree rooted in its land — is the Edenic restoration motif (Gen 2:8: YHWH planted a garden). The covenant land as YHWH&#8217;s own plantation, the people as his planted garden, the king as the one whose rule enables the undisturbed growth — this is the covenant ideal. Violent men will oppress them no more as they did previously.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8216;I will give you rest from all your enemies&#8217; — and then the pivot: &#8216;The LORD declares to you that the LORD will establish (<em>ʿāśāh</em>) a house for you.&#8217; The promised rest precedes the covenant announcement; the covenant promise is given in the context of the completed military program. The particle <em>wĕhiggîḏ lĕḵā YHWH kî-bayit yaʿăśeh-lĕḵā YHWH</em> — &#8216;YHWH declares to you that YHWH will build you a house.&#8217; The reversal is announced with formal solemnity: what David offered to do for YHWH, YHWH will do for David.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8216;He is the one who will build a house (<em>bayit</em>) for my name, and I will establish (<em>kûn</em>, H3559) the throne of his kingdom forever (<em>ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em>).&#8217; The threefold promise: (1) the son builds the temple (Solomon&#8217;s near fulfillment); (2) YHWH establishes the throne (the covenant security); (3) forever (the eschatological scope). <em>Kûn</em> (to establish/make firm) — from the same root as the name <em>Kĕnaan</em> (Canaan) and <em>kōhēn</em> (priest) — indicates secure, lasting establishment, not provisional arrangement. <em>ʿAḏ-ʿôlām</em> (&#8216;forever&#8217;) — the eschatological horizon that no Davidic descendant before Christ could reach.</p>",
    "14": "<p><em>ʾăni ʾehyeh-lô lĕʾāḇ wĕhûʾ yihyeh-lî lĕḇēn</em> — &#8216;I will be his father, and he will be my son.&#8217; The father-son formula is the adoption formula of the ancient Near East (parallel in Hittite king-lists and Egyptian coronation texts). In Israel, it means the king is YHWH&#8217;s adopted son at the anointing — Psalm 2:7 applies it to the coronation: &#8216;You are my son; today I have begotten you.&#8217; Hebrews 1:5 applies the same verse to Jesus, distinguishing Christ&#8217;s sonship from angelic status: no angel was ever addressed with this formula. The promise of discipline if the son does wrong (&#8216;with the rod of men&#8217;) is the covenant-father&#8217;s commitment to correction rather than abandonment.</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>wĕḥasdî lōʾ-yāsûr mimmennû kaʾăšer hăsirōṯî mēʿim šāʾûl ʾăšer hăsirōṯî millĕp̄ānêḵā</em> — &#8216;My steadfast love (<em>ḥeseḏ</em>) will not be taken from him, as I took it from Saul, whom I removed before you.&#8217; The contrast with Saul is the theological signature of the Davidic covenant: what Saul forfeited through disobedience (<em>ḥeseḏ</em> withdrawn), David&#8217;s heir will never forfeit. <em>Ḥeseḏ</em> (H2617, steadfast covenant love/loyalty) — the covenant&#8217;s most comprehensive term for YHWH&#8217;s binding commitment — is guaranteed unconditionally for the Davidic heir in a way it was not for Saul. The contrast Saul/David structures the entire rest of the Samuel narrative.</p>",
    "16": "<p><em>wĕneʾman bêtĕḵā ûmamlaktĕḵā ʿaḏ-ʿôlām lĕp̄ānêḵā kissĕʾăḵā yihyeh nāḵôn ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em> — &#8216;Your house and your kingdom will endure before me forever; your throne will be established (<em>kûn</em>) forever.&#8217; The fourfold covenant assurance: house (<em>bayit</em>), kingdom (<em>mamlāḵāh</em>), and throne (<em>kissēʾ</em>) are all established (<em>neʾman/nāḵôn</em>, from <em>ʾāman/kûn</em>) forever (<em>ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em> twice). The three-element royal formula (house-kingdom-throne) is the complete royal covenant structure. The double <em>ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em> signals that this is not conditional on performance but guaranteed by divine promise — the unconditional Davidic covenant.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Nathan speaks all these words to David according to &#8216;this whole vision&#8217; (<em>kĕkōl haddĕḇārîm hāʾēlleh ûḵĕkōl haḥizzāyôn hazzeh</em>). The double characterization — &#8216;all these words&#8217; and &#8216;this whole vision&#8217; — emphasizes the completeness of the transmission: Nathan conveys the entire revelation, nothing truncated. The word-vision tandem (<em>dāḇār</em> and <em>ḥizzāyôn</em>) describes the prophetic oracle as both verbal communication and visual revelation — the two modes of prophetic reception in the OT (Num 12:6: YHWH speaks to prophets in visions and dreams, but to Moses face to face).</p>",
    "18": "<p>David goes in and &#8216;sits before YHWH&#8217; (<em>wayyēšeḇ dāwid lip̄nê YHWH</em>) and prays. The posture of sitting before YHWH — rather than prostrating or standing — is unique in the OT for this context; it indicates the intimacy of a covenant son before the Father. The prayer begins: &#8216;Who am I, Lord YHWH, and what is my family, that you have brought me this far?&#8217; (<em>mî ʾānōḵî ʾăḏōnāy YHWH ûmî bêṯî</em>). The double humility question — who am I, who is my house? — is the covenant-consciousness of the one who knows that election is gift, not achievement.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8216;And yet this was too small a thing in your eyes, Lord YHWH. You have also spoken of your servant&#8217;s house in the distant future (<em>lĕmērāḥôq</em>) — and this is the instruction for humanity (<em>wĕzōʾṯ tôrat hāʾāḏām</em>), Lord YHWH.&#8217; The phrase <em>tôrat hāʾāḏām</em> (the instruction/law for humanity) is highly debated — it may mean &#8216;this is a charter for all humanity&#8217; (the Davidic covenant has implications beyond Israel) or &#8216;you have shown me the way things work for humans&#8217; (YHWH governs human affairs according to this covenant pattern). Either way, David grasps the eschatological scope: the covenant reaches into the distant future (<em>lĕmērāḥôq</em>) and its implications are universal.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8216;What more can David say to you? You know your servant, Lord YHWH.&#8217; (<em>wĕ-ʾattāh yāḏaʿtā ʾet-ʿaḇdeḵā</em>). The covenant-knowledge formula — YHWH knows David completely — renders further self-explanation unnecessary. The prayer makes no petition beyond acknowledgment; it is doxological recognition of what YHWH has already done. The echo of Psalm 139:1-4 (&#8216;You have searched me and known me... you know when I sit and when I rise; you perceive my thoughts from afar&#8217;) — this is the same divine knowledge before which all human words are secondary.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8216;For the sake of your servant and according to your own purpose (<em>ûḵĕlibbĕḵā ʿāśîṯā ʾet-kol-haggĕḏûlāh hazzōʾṯ</em>), you have done all this greatness.&#8217; David explicitly attributes YHWH&#8217;s action to YHWH&#8217;s own will and purpose, not to David&#8217;s merit. <em>Kĕlibbĕḵā</em> (&#8216;according to your heart&#8217;) — YHWH acted from his own inner purpose, not from external constraint or David&#8217;s worthiness. The same self-grounding of divine action in Eph 1:5,9: &#8216;according to his good pleasure&#8217; (<em>kata tēn eudokian tou thelēmatos autou</em>) — the divine will as its own sufficient cause.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&#8216;Therefore you are great, O Lord YHWH — there is no one like you, and there is no God besides you (<em>ʾên ʾĕlōhîm zûlāṯeḵā</em>), according to all we have heard with our ears.&#8217; The incomparability formula (<em>ʾên kāmôḵā</em>, there is none like you) — the OT&#8217;s standard declaration of YHWH&#8217;s uniqueness (Exod 15:11; Isa 44:6-8; Jer 10:6). The appeal to &#8216;all we have heard with our ears&#8217; grounds the praise in covenantal tradition — the accumulated testimony of YHWH&#8217;s acts heard in the covenant community. Personal doxology grounded in corporate covenant memory.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8216;And who is like your people Israel — the one nation on earth whom God went to redeem (<em>pādāh</em>, H6299) as his own people, to make a name for himself.&#8217; David praises YHWH for Israel&#8217;s election, using the Exodus-redemption verb <em>pādāh</em> (ransom/redeem). Israel&#8217;s uniqueness (<em>gôy ʾeḥāḏ</em>, one nation) is grounded not in their achievement but in YHWH&#8217;s redemptive act. &#8216;To make a name for himself&#8217; (<em>lāśûm lô šēm</em>) — YHWH&#8217;s redemption of Israel serves his own covenantal identity. Ezek 36:22-23 makes this explicit: YHWH acts for the sake of his holy name among the nations.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8216;You established (<em>wattĕkōnēn</em>) your people Israel as your own people forever (<em>ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em>), and you, YHWH, became their God.&#8217; The covenant-establishment formula (<em>kûn</em> again) applied to Israel: YHWH permanently confirmed Israel as his covenant people. The mutual possession formula — &#8216;my people&#8217; and &#8216;their God&#8217; — is the covenant formula from Sinai (Exod 6:7; Lev 26:12; Jer 31:33; Rev 21:3: &#8216;They will be his people, and God himself will be with them and be their God&#8217;). David&#8217;s prayer recapitulates the entire covenant structure: YHWH established Israel, and the reciprocal relationship is permanent.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8216;And now, Lord YHWH, confirm forever the word you have spoken concerning your servant and his house — do as you have spoken (<em>ʿăśēh kaʾăšer dibbartā</em>).&#8217; The prayer&#8217;s petition is simply that YHWH do what he said. <em>Qûm</em> (H6965, to rise/confirm/establish) — &#8216;cause your word to stand.&#8217; The covenant request that YHWH be faithful to his own word is the highest form of prayer: not asking YHWH to do something new but to fulfill what he has already committed to. The prayer asks nothing more than YHWH&#8217;s faithfulness to his own promise.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8216;May your name be magnified (<em>wĕyigdal šimkā</em>) forever, so that it will be said, YHWH of hosts is God over Israel.&#8217; The prayer&#8217;s ultimate goal is YHWH&#8217;s magnification — the covenant&#8217;s purpose is YHWH&#8217;s glory, not merely Israel&#8217;s blessing or David&#8217;s dynasty. The Johannine formulation: &#8216;Father, glorify your name&#8217; (John 12:28); &#8216;that they may all be one... so that the world may believe that you have sent me&#8217; (John 17:21). The prayer for YHWH&#8217;s name to be magnified through the covenant fulfillment is the deepest structure of both David&#8217;s prayer and Jesus&#8217;s high-priestly prayer.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&#8216;For you, YHWH of hosts, God of Israel, have revealed this to your servant (<em>gālîṯā ʾet-ʾōzen ʿaḇdeḵā</em>, lit. uncovered your servant&#8217;s ear) — I will build you a house.&#8217; The intimate revelation formula (uncovering the ear for private disclosure) grounds the prayer: David prays boldly because YHWH has disclosed what he is going to do. The NT boldness in prayer rests on the same foundation: Jesus revealed to his disciples everything the Father told him (John 15:15); the Spirit reveals the deep things of God (1 Cor 2:10). Disclosed revelation is the ground of confident petition.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&#8216;And now, Lord YHWH, you are God; your words are true (<em>ʾattāh hāʾĕlōhîm ûdĕḇārêḵā yihyû ʾĕmeṯ</em>), and you have made this good promise to your servant.&#8217; The identification of YHWH&#8217;s words as <em>ʾĕmeṯ</em> (H571, truth/faithfulness/reliability) — the root word of &#8216;amen.&#8217; YHWH&#8217;s words are <em>ʾĕmeṯ</em>: they correspond to reality, they fulfill what they promise, they can be relied upon with absolute confidence. Jesus&#8217;s self-identification as &#8216;the way, the truth (<em>hē alētheia</em>), and the life&#8217; (John 14:6) and &#8216;the Amen, the faithful and true witness&#8217; (Rev 3:14) are the incarnation of this quality David confesses about YHWH&#8217;s word.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&#8216;Therefore be pleased to bless the house of your servant, that it may stand before you forever (<em>lip̄nêḵā ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em>), for you, Lord YHWH, have spoken, and with your blessing the house of your servant will be blessed forever.&#8217; The closing petition seals the prayer with the same word that sealed the oracle: <em>ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em> (forever). The prayer&#8217;s final logic: because YHWH spoke, and because YHWH&#8217;s words are <em>ʾĕmeṯ</em>, the blessing is certain — David asks YHWH to do what YHWH has already promised. The covenant certainty is the ground of the prayer and its answer; YHWH&#8217;s commitment is the premise from which the petition follows.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('original', '2samuel')
    merge_comm(c, ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('original', '2samuel', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in ORIGINAL.values())
    print(f'2samuel mkt-original: wrote {total} verses across ch 4-7')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
